<!-- PHILOSOPHY -->
<section class="philosophy reveal">
  <div>
    <p class="philosophy-eyebrow">Why workshops</p>
    <h2>Knowledge that lives<br>in your <em>hands</em>, not<br>just your head</h2>
  </div>
  <div>
    <p>There is a version of wellness education that fills you with information and sends you home with a notepad and a vague feeling that you should do something differently. I am not interested in that version.</p>
    <p>Every workshop I design starts from a single question: <em>what will this person actually do differently on Monday morning?</em> That question shapes the format, the content, the materials, and the pace. Some workshops you leave with a tin of something you blended yourself. Some you leave with a protocol you have tested on your own pulse. All of them, you leave with something you can use.</p>
    <p>Groups are small — never more than twelve — because learning about your own health is personal, and it deserves to happen in a space where questions are welcome and there is enough time to actually think.</p>
  </div>
</section>

